<paragraph blockId="38.[120,1225,700,1137]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Nest closures observed by J.G.R. and C.J.P. were flush with the exposed surface and were not implanted with pebbles or other debris as reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Westrich, P." box="[826,1016,849,876]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref24301" refString="Westrich, P. 1989. Die Wildbienen Baden-Wurttembergs. Allgemeiner Teil: Lebensraume, Verhalten, Okologie und Schutz; Spezieller Teil: Die Gattungen und Arten. Stuttgart: Verlag Eugen Ulmer. 972 pp." type="book" year="1989">Westrich (1989)</bibRefCitation>
and as discussed recently by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozen, J. G., Jr. &amp; H. H. Go" box="[257,483,887,914]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref23678" refString="Rozen, J. G., Jr., and H. H. Go. 2015. Descriptions of the egg and mature larva of the bee Chelostoma (Prochelostoma) philadelphi with additional notes on nesting biology (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae: Megachilinae: Osmiini). American Museum Novitates 3844: 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="2015">Rozen et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[120,1225,700,1137]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
The rest of the information correlates well with the nest descriptions provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Westrich, P." pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref24301" refString="Westrich, P. 1989. Die Wildbienen Baden-Wurttembergs. Allgemeiner Teil: Lebensraume, Verhalten, Okologie und Schutz; Spezieller Teil: Die Gattungen und Arten. Stuttgart: Verlag Eugen Ulmer. 972 pp." type="book" year="1989">Westrich (1989)</bibRefCitation>
. Both he and 
<bibRefCitation author="Muller, A. &amp; A. Krebs &amp; F. Amiet" box="[356,578,961,988]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref23158" refString="Muller, A., A. Krebs, and F. Amiet. 1997. Bienen, mitteleuropaische Gattungen, Lebensweise, Beobachtung. Munchen: Naturbuch Verlag. 384 pp." type="book" year="1997">MÃ¼ller et al. (1997)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that this species also nests in vacated beetle burrows in old wood and in stems of such plants as blackberries. They also noted that cells were arranged in linear series separated by septa of resin, sometimes with empty chambers between cells. Nest closures were also made of resin in which were implants of pebbles, wood fiber, or other debris.
</paragraph>
